## description: TypeScript standards for the SafeStop project. Defines typing conventions, strict mode, shared types, naming, and best practices.

# TypeScript Rules

## Objective

All TypeScript code must prioritize:

- type safety;
- readability;
- maintainability;
- predictability;
- reuse.

TypeScript exists to prevent errors before runtime.

Never bypass the type system to "make the code work".

---

# Strict Mode

Always assume the project uses TypeScript in strict mode.

The generated code must be compatible with:

- `"strict": true`
- `"noImplicitAny": true`
- `"strictNullChecks": true`

Never rely on relaxed compiler options.

---

# Never use `any`

Never introduce `any` unless explicitly requested.

Prefer, in this order:

1. existing domain type;
2. shared type;
3. generic;
4. `unknown`;
5. discriminated union.

`any` is always the last resort.

---

# Prefer Existing Types

Before creating a new interface or type:

1. Search the project.
2. Search `packages/types`.
3. Search shared models.
4. Search Supabase generated types.

Avoid duplicated definitions.

---

# Shared Types

Domain types must live in shared packages whenever they are used by more than one application.

Examples:

- User
- Occurrence
- Notification
- Organization
- Company
- Attachment

Do not duplicate these types inside `apps/mobile` or `apps/web`.

---

# Domain First

Always model business concepts.

Good:

```ts
type OccurrenceStatus = ...
```

Bad:

```ts
type ScreenData = ...
```

Types should represent the business, not the UI.

---

# Interfaces vs Type

Use:

`interface`

for:

- object contracts;
- public APIs;
- class contracts.

Use:

`type`

for:

- unions;
- mapped types;
- utility types;
- aliases;
- intersections.

---

# Enums

Avoid TypeScript enums unless required.

Prefer literal unions.

Good:

```ts
type Severity = "LOW" | "MEDIUM" | "HIGH" | "CRITICAL";
```

Instead of:

```ts
enum Severity { ... }
```

Literal unions are easier to infer, serialize and validate.

---

# Discriminated Unions

Whenever an object has multiple states, prefer discriminated unions.

Example:

```ts
type SyncState =
  | { state: "pending" }
  | { state: "syncing" }
  | { state: "failed"; reason: string }
  | { state: "completed" };
```

Avoid multiple unrelated booleans.

Bad:

```ts
isLoading;
isPending;
isSuccess;
isError;
```

---

# Optional Properties

Only make a property optional if it is truly optional in the business domain.

Do not use optional properties simply to silence TypeScript.

---

# Null vs Undefined

Prefer:

`undefined`

for absent values.

Use:

`null`

only when required by external APIs or database semantics.

---

# Function Return Types

Exported functions should always declare an explicit return type.

Example:

```ts
export function createOccurrence(): Promise<Occurrence>;
```

Avoid relying solely on inference for public APIs.

---

# Async Functions

Always return typed Promises.

Good:

```ts
Promise<void>;

Promise<User>;

Promise<Result<T>>;
```

Never return implicit Promise<any>.

---

# Generic Types

Use generics only when they improve reuse.

Avoid unnecessary complexity.

Good:

```ts
Result<T>;
```

Bad:

```ts
Result<T, U, K, V, X>;
```

---

# Utility Types

Prefer native utility types.

Examples:

- Partial
- Pick
- Omit
- Record
- Required
- Readonly

Avoid recreating existing utility types.

---

# Zod

Validation schemas are the source of truth.

Whenever possible:

```ts
type FormData = z.infer<typeof schema>;
```

Never duplicate the same structure manually.

---

# React Components

Always type component props.

Good:

```ts
interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
}
```

Avoid anonymous prop objects.

---

# Hooks

Every exported hook must declare its return type.

Custom hooks should expose stable and predictable APIs.

---

# Event Handlers

Always type event handlers.

Avoid implicit event types.

---

# Error Handling

Prefer typed errors.

Do not throw strings.

Good:

```ts
throw new Error("...");
```

---

# Imports

Prefer importing types separately when appropriate.

Example:

```ts
import type { User } from "@/types";
```

Avoid importing runtime values when only the type is needed.

---

# Naming Conventions

Types:

```text
Occurrence
Notification
User
```

Interfaces:

```text
OccurrenceProps
NotificationPayload
```

Generics:

```text
T
TData
TError
TResult
```

Booleans:

```text
isLoading
isReleased
hasPermission
canApprove
```

---

# Readability

Prefer clear code over clever code.

Avoid deeply nested generic expressions.

Avoid over-engineering.

---

# SafeStop Standards

Every type must reflect the business language of the project.

Prefer names such as:

- Occurrence
- Notification
- IMSReference
- MDHOAssessment
- CorrectiveAction
- ReleaseDecision

Avoid generic names such as:

- Item
- Data
- Object
- Info

---

# Before Creating New Types

Always verify whether the type already exists.

Priority:

1. packages/types
2. Supabase generated types
3. Shared domain models
4. Existing feature types

Only create a new type when no reusable alternative exists.

---

# Final Rule

Every line of TypeScript should make the code:

- safer;
- easier to understand;
- easier to maintain;
- easier to refactor.

Never weaken the type system for convenience.
